"21404","10/7/2004 14:40","04MADRID3937","Embassy Madrid","CONFIDENTIAL","04SECSTATE209905","This record is a partial extract of the original cable. The full text of the original cable is not available.


 ","C O N F I D E N T I A L MADRID 003937 
 
SIPDIS 
 
E.O. 12958: DECL: 10/15/2014 
TAGS: ECIN, PREL, EU, TU, CY, SP 
SUBJECT: SPAIN: APPROACH TO EU MEMBERS ON AID, TRADE FOR 
NORTH CYPRUS 
 
REF: SECSTATE 209905 
 
Classified By: Economic Counselor Whitney Baird for reasons 1.2 (b) and 
 (d) 
 
We delivered reftel points to Ministry of Foreign Affairs 
Deputy Director for EU Policy Planning Enrique Mora 
Benavente.  Mora Benavente said that Spain is highly 
supportive of extending trade concessions and financial 
assistance to the Turkish Cypriots.  However, he noted that 
in the recent EU meetings on this issue, Greece and Cyprus 
opposed allowing EU trade relations with North Cyprus, a 
change requiring unanimous consent.  Mora Benavente noted 
that the current EU goal is to extend economic aid as soon as 
possible, and then open the door to trade considerations when 
the Greeks and Greek Cypriots are willing.  Spain will 
support the $259 million Euro aid package when it comes to a 
vote.  E.U. assistance to North Cyprus does not require 
unanimous consent and Mora Benavente expects the aid package 
to be approved. 
ARGYROS 
